Eight songs of a spiritual nature.
Buchanan is widely-regarded as the most distinguished of Gaelic hymn-writers.
Buchanan was an excellent scholar and an Enlightenment man&nbsp;with a passionate commitment to the Gaelic culture.
Buchanan was equally at home in English and Gaelic. He drew on the tradition of spiritual verse within the Highlands but also utilised other models, borrowing extensively from the works of Watts, Young, Blair and Thomson. When evangelicalism spread through the Highlands, his work provided a Gaelic context and played a crucial role second only to the Gaelic Bible and the Metrical Psalter.
Buchanan wrote in clear, communicative Gaelic with some traces of Perthshire Gaelic.
Extensive use of the imagery of the natural world makes his work an important source of vocabulary relating to the land, landscape, etc.
Buchanan touches on the nature of God, the life of Jesus, Judgement, the importance of being a spiritual person, and the need to prepare for death. He also criticises those who put too much emphasis on worldly goods.
His use of the imagery of nature to convey spiritual meaning introduced a new dimension to Gaelic religious verse in this early Evangelical phase in the Highlands.','short_title' => 'The Spiritual Songs of Dugald Buchanan ','gaelic_text_by' => 'N/A','illustrator' => 'N/A'),
