  array('reference_number' => '193','title' => 'The Book of the Dean of Lismore','author' => 'N/A','editor' => 'Duncan MacGregor and James MacGregor (The Dean of Lismore)','date_of_edition' => 'N/A','publisher' => 'N/A','place_published' => 'N/A','volume' => 'N/A','genre' => 'Literature','medium' => 'Prose & Verse','rating' => 'A
A highly significant text, one of the most important Gaelic manuscripts to survive.
Shows that Irish-Scottish literary contacts were being maintained fduring the last century of the Lordship of the Isles and after its demise.&nbsp;Bardic verse shows the specific parts of Ireland and Scotland in which the compilers of the MS were interested and to which they had ready access.
Some texts have been emended by the compilers in ways which were new to Gaelic and suggest a distinctly post-Medieval interest in transforming a number of versions into a composite &lsquo;best&rsquo; text. Not found in Gaelic before 1600. Seems to be an attempt to&nbsp;produce a single text of an eclectic type.
The range of contents cannot be paralleled in any other collection from Scotland or Ireland. Many unique items.
The exemplary quality of the most significant specimens of the various genres suggests that the compilers&rsquo; project was a bold and ambitious one. Scribes may have been aware that the Gaelic world was on the cusp of change. There are hints in some literary genres of a pessimistic attitude towards the long-term survival of Gaelic culture.
The adoption of a Scots-based orthography by the compilers of the MS marks an important development in the relationship between Gaelic and Scots language and culture.','short_title' => 'Bk. Dean Lismore','gaelic_text_by' => 'N/A','illustrator' => 'N/A'),
