Monthly periodical which ran from May 1829 to May 1831, and which contained a variety of stories, articles, and verse.
This is the most important of the nineteenth century periodicals, and it set the standard for many later publications. It dealt with new and modern topics in Gaelic, introducing new terminology, and widening the range of&nbsp;written Gaelic.
Subject-matter of articles includes contemporary technology, world geography, and Scottish history.
Some articles give advice and information on various subjects including crofting, fishing, and health.
There are some religious articles and articles relating to superstition and to the otherworld.
There are some articles about the Gaelic language.
There are a number of stories, some of which have strong religious overtones.
Contains some poems and hymns.','short_title' => 'An Teachdaire Gaelach Vol 1','gaelic_text_by' => 'N/A','illustrator' => 'N/A'),
